english:
  title: A Refutation of the Buddha's Begging for Alms
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: "Food is the greatest matter under heaven. One cannot survive a single day without eating, yet one must never eat in a way that lacks integrity. To go without food harms one's very life; to eat without principle harms righteousness itself. In the Eight Policies of the Hong Fan, the provision of food and goods comes first. Among the five teachings for the people, food holds the foremost place. When Zigong inquired of governance, the Master replied by speaking of sufficient food. Thus the sages of old understood that the livelihood of the people cannot rest even for a day without sustenance. They devoted themselves to teaching agriculture, establishing systems of tribute and taxation, ensuring provisions for the state and its ceremonies, providing for guests, caring for the widowed, orphaned, elderly, and young—so that no one would suffer want or hunger. How far-reaching was the sage's concern for the people.\n\nFrom the highest—the Son of Heaven, the lords and ministers—who feed themselves through governing the people, to the lowest—farmers, artisans, and merchants who feed themselves through diligent labor, to those in between—the scholars who practice filial piety at home and respect abroad, preserving the Way of former kings while teaching later generations, thus earning their sustenance—the ancient sages understood that one cannot live even a day eating with compromised principles. Therefore, from top to bottom, each has his proper role, receiving heaven's nourishment. The sage's protection of the people was thus complete. Those who fall outside this order are villainous folk, whom the law of kings must execute without pardon.\n\nThe Vajra Sutra states: \"At that time, the World-Honored One, when the time for eating came, donned his robes, took up his bowl, entered the city of Sravasti, and begged for food within its walls.\"\n\nNow, this Shakyamuni claims that men and women living together is unrighteous, removing himself from human relationships, abandoning the work of cultivation, severing the very root of life's continuation. Seeking to transform the customs of the world through his Way—if his doctrine were truly followed, there would be no people under heaven. How then could anyone give alms? If there were no people, there would be no food. How could one beg for sustenance?\n\nShakyamuni was the son of a king of the Western regions. He rejected his father's throne as unrighteous and departed—yet he is no one who governs the people. He rejected men tilling fields and women weaving as unrighteous—yet where is his diligence? Without father and son, lord and subject, husband and wife, he is no preserver of the ancient Way. This man, even eating a single grain of rice per day, consumes only with compromised principles. If his Way were truly followed, one should eat nothing, like an earthworm, and nothing more. Why then does he beg and eat?\n\nDoes eating through one's own labor become unrighteous, while begging makes it righteous? The Buddha's words lack both propriety and reason—open any text and you will see it at once. Therefore I set forth this refutation.\n\nIn the beginning, the Buddha's followers merely begged for their food. Yet righteous people censured them for this lack of principle without the slightest excuse. But now? They dwell in grand halls and layered mansions, clothed richly and fed abundantly, enjoying comforts like a king's favor. They possess vast fields and numerous servants; their records overflow like government documents, their supplies rushing forth more urgently than official duties. Where now is their Way of cutting through affliction and transcending the world, of purity and sparse desire? They not only squander resources while sitting idle, but cloak themselves in false piety, offering elaborate provisions—food scattered about, fine silks torn asunder for ornamental banners and standards—depleting in a single day the accumulated wealth of ten common households. Alas, having abandoned righteousness and reason, they have become parasites upon human relationships; by despoiling heaven's creation, they are great worms devouring heaven and earth itself.\n\nZhang Zai said: \"When those above have no ritual to prevent deception, and those below have no learning to illuminate what is hidden, how can one who is not of uncommon talent, free from fear even in solitude, and perfectly sincere in self-trust, hope to stand firm in such circumstances and contend with others over right and wrong, calculating gain and loss?\" \n\nAlas, that the ancient worthies sighed so deeply—was this mere chance? Was this mere chance?"
  footnotes:
    - 'Hong Fan (洪範): One of the foundational texts in Chinese political philosophy, part of the Book of History, outlining eight governmental policies.'
    - 'Zigong (子貢): A renowned disciple of Confucius, known for his wisdom and ethical conduct.'
    - 'Vajra Sutra (金剛經): A fundamental Buddhist scripture, here cited to illustrate Shakyamuni''s practice of begging.'
    - 'Shakyamuni: The historical Buddha, Gautama Buddha.'
    - 'Zhang Zai (張子): An influential Neo-Confucian philosopher of the Song dynasty.'
